# Study 2
* Genesis 1:1-2:3
## Summary
The Bible tells the story of how *God raises up a ruler to redeem us and restore what we have ruined, for his renown*. Genesis 1 begins the story by telling us about God and his creation of the world and of humanity. 

God is revealed as the creator and therefore ruler over all things. He creates matter, establishes order and entrusts humans with the care of his world. The life-support systems of air, water and land provide creation’s abundance of living species with sustenance and space to live. God creatively transforms the formless void into a magnificent, ordered, balanced universe. Here is the stage on which the drama of history will be played.

This is our introduction to God and how he works: He creates methodically in 6 successive days, building to a climax in the rest enjoyed on the 7th day. So too God will develop the drama of history through successive epochs, to the thrilling finale when all will bow to Christ and enjoy the eternal rest of a restored creation.   

## Introduction

Genesis 1:1-2:4 is a theological, not a scientific account of the world’s beginning. It addresses questions of origin, purpose and value, not of process. It is true, but the phrase ‘literally true’ may not be helpful. Different forms of literature teach truth in different ways. Robert Burns wrote truth when he penned the line ‘*my love is like a red, red, rose,*’ in spite of the fact that the woman he adored did not have a thin, green, spiky body, and a puffy red face… Genesis 1 is not intended to be a scientific textbook and if we read it as such we will miss the glorious truths which it does teach.

### 1:1-2 God and Nothing
The Bible does not begin with humanity or even the world, but with God. Before there is any physical matter, there is God. Verse 1 may be a summary of the chapter but is better understood as the first act of creation: a precursor to the action of 2-31. Here we see God create the raw material from which he will shape our breathtaking, intricate, complex universe.

### 1:3-25 Order and Goodness
The bulk of the chapter takes place in the carefully structured narrative recording days\* 1-6 with the repeated pattern of words and phrases (*‘said’, ‘separated’, ‘called’, ‘saw’, ‘God’, ‘good’, ‘evening’, ‘morning’,*  ‘*day*’). This pattern and rhythm is observable to us, but is even more evident in the Hebrew. We see that there is order and pattern and purpose to how God works. 

God creates and God evaluates. He has a concern for the goodness of what he has made. He is judging the world to be morally and physically good.

The table in the questions shows how the 6 days are structured: on days 1-3 God forms or separates to create structures. Then on days 4-6 he fills those structures.   
There is a sense of growth and development to the chapter, as the cosmos goes from formless and empty to teeming with abundant life.

\*Christians differ as to whether the days are to be taken literally. The view that they are a literary device, or describe periods of time is not just an attempt to fit with the teachings of modern science. Augustine suggested this back in the 4th century. There are strong reasons in the text itself to adopt this view: i. Verse 1 is outside of the 6 days and this contains the creation of the world. ii. The same word for ‘day’ appears in 2:4 in the singular ‘*this is the account of the heavens and the earth on the day God created them.*’ iii. Day one records the creation of light, and is called ‘*the first day,*’ but the sun and moon aren’t created until day 4\. It’s hard to see how there can be a day in the normal sense of the word without a sun for the earth to orbit around… It seems much better to take the ‘*days*’ as a literary device to divide up the account of creation.

### 1:26-2:4 Humanity and Rest
The narrative changes at verse 26\. Everything slows down as we focus in on the creation of humanity. Everything is made by God, but only humanity bears God’s image. The Hebrew word translated “*man*” is “*Adam.*” Image of God relates to us reflecting God, and ruling the world for God.

We learn here that humans are ‘*neither gods nor dogs.*’ We are not gods, for we are created beings, made ‘*in \[God’s\] likeness,*’ not the same as God. We are created by and dependent on God. Neither are we just another animal. While we are part of the creation, we are also made in the image of God (Psalm 8 captures this tension beautifully). There is enormous debate about image of God. What is clear from this account is that in some ways we reflect God. We have ears because he hears, eyes because he sees, etc. Likewise we are made male and female because there is complexity and plurality in God (and because he creates life, just as man and woman are able to do). Verse 26 does not teach that men and women are only half complete and need to come together to fully bear the image of God. Rather it teaches men and women alike fully bear the image of God.

The other aspect to which image of God is tied is our rule over creation. Verses 26 and 28 both tie image of God to a god-reflecting role of filling and ruling the earth. The word ‘*subdue*’ in verse 28 must not be taken out of context. Everything in chapter 1 shows God’s delight in and care for creation. This is not a mandate for exploitation and destruction, but a command to cultivate and bring fruitfulness and order. Note at this point that all humans bear the image of God equally. Here is the ultimate ground for human rights and equality. 

It’s easy to miss the implications of the first thing God does when he has created humans – he speaks to us. This shows God wants to relate to us, and that he has made us able to relate to and understand him.

The 6th day ends with a different evaluation from God – with humanity in place to rule and cultivate the world it is not just ‘*good*,’ but ‘*very good*.’

#### Rest
The climax of the account of creation is not humanity but the Sabbath rest. God does not stop all activity (the Bible makes this clear in a number of places, such as John 5:17; Romans 8:28; Hebrews 1:3). What he stops is the ‘*work of creating*,’ because it is complete (Astonishingly the word used for God’s work is the same as for ordinary human work in Exodus 20:8-11. Work is part of what it means to be made in the image of God\!) Sabbath is not a day for ceasing all activity, but a day for enjoying a creation which is as it should be.

#### Rule
Ephesians 1 told us that God’s plan is to unite all things under the rule of Christ. Genesis 1 establishes God’s right to rule as it details his creation of all things.  

#### Word
Acts 13 told us that God’s plan progresses through the fulfilment of his promises. Genesis 1 encourages us to trust God’s promises by showing us the power of his words. His words shape reality. When he speaks, creation happens. Scientists like John Lennox also observe that creation by word fits the reality of a universe where the basic building blocks of life are the language / information of DNA.

#### Trinity
The term ‘*Trinity*’ does not appear in the Bible. However the truth of one God in three persons is there throughout. It is hinted at right here in the first verses of the first chapter: God is named in verse 1\. In verse 2 we are told of the Spirit of God. Where though is God the Son? In verse 3, God speaks creation into being. In John 1:1-5 Jesus, the Son is introduced to us as the word of God. So we find God, Word and Spirit. It should be no surprise then that when God speaks to create mankind in verse 26, he speaks in the plural ‘*let us make mankind in our image.*’ 

It would be wrong to claim Genesis 1 teaches explicitly that God is Triune. However it is undeniable that this chapter hints at and fits with the doctrine of the Trinity.

## What
The God of the Bible created all things by his word. He created it with order and beauty.   

## So What
Here is a God to be worshipped and obeyed – a God of infinite power who speaks and the cosmos comes into being\!

## Questions

* What difference would it make to life if there was no God and the world had just always existed?

### Read Genesis 1:1-25

* What truth does the Bible affirm in the very first verse?  
* What two things are we told about the physical creation at the beginning of v.2?  
* Fill in the table below. How do the 6 days of creation address formlessness and emptiness?

| Day | Form / Separate | Day | Fill |
| :---: | ----- | :---: | ----- |
| **1** | Light / Dark  | **4** | Sun, moon & stars |
| **2** | Sky / Waters  | **5** | Birds & fish |
| **3** | Seas / Land and vegetation  | **6** | Animals & humans |

* What does this account tell us about the value of the physical world? (what does God say at the end of each day?)  
* What are the implications of this for how we relate to the natural world?

### Read Genesis 1:26-2:3

* What is different about these last verses?   
* What do we learn about humanity?  
* How does this help us find a stable ground for our sense of identity and self-worth?  
* What does image of God seem to involve? (Look in particular at the commands that come straight after it)

* What is the climax of the creation account?  
* What does God rest from on the 7th day? So what things is God still doing? (*Hebrews 1:3; Romans 8:28; etc*)  
* How should we live in the light of the pattern of work and rest that is sown into creation?  
* How is the God of Genesis 1 different from a Star Wars-esque force?  
* List all the things we learn about God in this account
    * (*creates; outside of creation; speaks; makes value judgement; enjoys; relational*)  
* What is an appropriate response to this?

* Why might people find Genesis 1 offensive?  
* Ephesians 1 told us that God’s plan is to unite all things under the rule of Christ. What right does God have to rule?  
* Acts 13 told us God makes promises and fulfils them. How does Genesis 1 deepen our trust in his ability to fulfil his promises?
